<br>
Attitude is alot but it ain't everything. There are bounderies to what people can do like physical health and mental abilities. Attitude can tune down those flaws a bit but not in drastic measures. Some people have less opportunities then other and that is only based on their physical and mental and not even taken there social enviroment into account.<br>
<br>
In Kebkin case he passed certain bounderies that are not so normal for certain people. He was smart enough to get accepted into university. He had the physical stamina to work 40 hours a day and follow a full course. He had the mental focus and capacities to under dose very difficult circumstance to pass his course. He had the physical abilities and mental profile to join the army. He was again smart enought to get his master.<br>
<br>
If Kebkin had astma would he have achieved the same even with his positive attitude? Would he have been where he is now? He would be smart enough to be a software engineer but serious doubt he would have reached this way without external help and only positive attitude.<br>
<br>
Attitude are very important but they can only overcome certain physical and mental problems. Each human is unique and each case if different. So find it unrealistic and blunt to say I have no sympathy for the poor because they only got themselves to blame because you could do it without external help.<br>
<br>
