Siffo, It's not that hard to understand if you really want to. This &quot;nonsense&quot; has been real trouble since the beginning of industrialization. Money calls more money, and money is not produced fast enough to compensate that effect. That's why you have to artificially regulate the market with anti-trust laws and tax brackets. If you don't - well, most of a country's money will end up in too few hands and even democracy could be in danger then. <br>
<br>
A practical example: In 1974 the richest 5 percent of American families earned 14.8 percent of total U.S. income; by 1998 their share had risen to 20.7 percent. Now imagine that this becomes a 60 percent in 50 years. You really don't see a problem there? <br>
